More on Humane
--------------

Benjamin Sandofsky, a former Apple employee, wrote a blog post entitled, Wh=
y You Can=E2=80=99t Build Apple with Venture Capital ( https://www.sandofsk=
y.com/humane/ ).

Only hubris can explain Humane=E2=80=99s dumbest product decision: a mandat=
ory $24/mo subscription that uses a separate phone number. Set aside the mo=
ney, nobody wants to manage two numbers! I have two email addresses and reg=
ret it whenever I fill out a form. I can picture the Humane product meeting=
 in my head. =E2=80=9CWhen we released the iPhone, we didn=E2=80=99t design=
 it as an accessory for your current phone. It had to be so amazing that us=
ers will be ready to go all-in. We cannot compromise Ai Pin by making it an=
 accessory. We must burn the ships.=E2=80=9D The flaw in this reasoning is =
that everything before the iPhone sucked. People were happy to switch to a =
smartphone, aside from $600 price tag which was hard to swallow.

Today we are so reliant on smart phones that abandoning them would upend ou=
r lives. My brokerage account uses a bespoke authentication app, so without=
 my phone and that very specific app, I can=E2=80=99t access that money. Th=
at would be solved if my brokerage firm ported their authenticator to the A=
i Pin, but that will never, ever happen. It=E2=80=99s a credit to the ridic=
ulous momentum of the first iPhone that Apple convinced so many developers =
to learn a completely new set of skills, and those developers have now spen=
t 16 years in this ecosystem. Why waste time and energy learning a new plat=
form when it doesn=E2=80=99t look like there=E2=80=99s going to be a market=
 for their apps?

A better strategy for AI Pin 1.0 would have been to release it as an access=
ory that pairs with your iPhone. Drop the cell connection to improve batter=
y life and bring down costs. If users bring their own carrier, there=E2=80=
=99s fewer complaints about dropped connections. While we=E2=80=99re cuttin=
g features, drop the camera. How many people want to take photos that they =
can=E2=80=99t frame ahead of time? Save money on parts, and use that space =
to fit more battery. Lower costs opens things up to more users, which entic=
e third-party developers to get into the ground floor of the next big thing=
. Instead, Humane tried to cosplay as Apple, adopting its =E2=80=9CMy way o=
r the highway=E2=80=9D attitude without any of Apple=E2=80=99s leverage tha=
t makes it work=E2=80=A6

I blame the team=E2=80=99s nostalgia. They clearly wants to recreate the Ap=
ple from 2007, but that=E2=80=99s impossible under a venture capital constr=
aints and without the momentum of Apple. Contrary to what Imran, Ken, and I=
=E2=80=99m sure many others at Humane believe, the iPhone didn=E2=80=99t be=
gin with their work in the 2000=E2=80=99s on Project Purple. It began in 19=
76 with the Apple computer, and the decades of goodwill it built up in cons=
umers. The project was spearheaded by a guy ready to waste billions in iPod=
 revenue if it helped achieve his vision, and he answered to nobody. It cam=
e together at the perfect point in time, when everyone knew the power of th=
e Internet, but there wasn=E2=80=99t a way to carry the whole experience in=
 your pocket. You can=E2=80=99t replicate all these factors in a few years,=
 no matter how much money a VC throws at you.

Sandofsky makes a lot of good points, but he misses an important one: the i=
Pod worked with both Windows and the Mac, and, crucially, so did the iPhone=
. In fact, a Windows or Mac computer was required to even set up the first =
several generations of iPhones (the first iPhone to not require iTunes on a=
 Windows or Mac computer was the iPhone 4S in 2011). Just as offloading lib=
rary management to iTunes allowed the iPod user interface to be simplified,=
 offloading things like contact, photo, and music syncing to a computer all=
owed the iPhone to be much more usable. Then, over time, Apple built up the=
 infrastructure (particularly iCloud) that allowed the iPhone to stand alon=
e.

Humane, however, by virtue of trying to replace a phone, dramatically incre=
ased the number of things it might do poorly, while crowding out the focus =
=E2=80=94 both in terms of hardware and software =E2=80=94=C2=A0necessary t=
o do one thing exceptionally well.

Limitless
---------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/4/15/24130832/limitless-ai-p=
endant-wearable-meetings ) :

The Limitless Pendant doesn=E2=80=99t exactly scream =E2=80=9CAI.=E2=80=9D =
As Dan Siroker, the CEO of the company behind the new device, lifts it up t=
o show me over Zoom, the round, rubbery-looking gizmo reminds me more of an=
 old-school clippable Fitbit. But what Siroker is actually showing me is a =
device that can be clipped onto your shirt or worn on a string around your =
neck that is meant to record everything you hear =E2=80=94 and then use AI =
to help you remember and make sense of it.

The Limitless Pendant is part of the whole Limitless system, which the comp=
any is launching today. (Oh, and in case you=E2=80=99re wondering: yes, it=
=E2=80=99s very much a reference to the movie.) Siroker=E2=80=99s last AI p=
roduct, Rewind, was an app that ran on your computer and would record your =
screen and other data in order to help you remember every tab, every song, =
every meeting, everything you do on your computer. (When the company first =
teased the Limitless Pendant, it was actually called the Rewind Pendant.) L=
imitless has similar aims, but instead of just running on your computer, it=
=E2=80=99s meant to collect data in the cloud and the real world, too, and =
make it all available to you on any device. Rewind is still around, for the=
 folks who want the all-local, one-computer approach =E2=80=94 but Siroker =
says the cross-platform opportunity is much bigger.

The Limitless Pendant is another =E2=80=9CAI=E2=80=9D wearable that is taki=
